Basics: Pulse Width Modulation (PWM)
Typical: A way for MCU to
generate an analog voltage.
Motor control: Enables multiple
modes of control (analog,
phase/en, polarity...)
Easily attened using a ca pacitor
as a low pass lter, or simply
relying on the physical process.
Average voltage = 5V Duty cycle
Parameters:
Signal period/frequency
Pulse width
Duty cycle
3
Exercise 7: Controlling the Serv o
Some servo systems can be controled with PWM, or "servo signal" in the
hobby RC world.
The angle of the servo is determined by the pulse wi dth (1.5 m s
corresponds to centre position).
The servo is controlled using a 50 Hz PWM signal
(period T =
1
f
=
1
50Hz
= 20ms )
By varying the pulse width we can control the angle.
The pulse width must never be outside the range 0.9-2.1 ms.
- Make sure your driver complies with the specs before connecting the servo.
4
Servo Positions and PWM
Information is encoded in the puls e width, not duty cycle or PWM frequency.
This seems to be an agreed upon (quasi) standard in the hobby industry.
5
How to generate a PWM signal: Two alternatives
RECOMMENDE D: PWM peripheral (datasheet chapter 38)
- Fewest lines of code and fewer registers needed.
- Need to use the 5V level-shifted PIN44 and PIN45 on the shield.
Timer Counter peripheral (datasheet chapter 36)
- Similar to how its done in node one for ADC clock: Counter with compare
that resets pin.
- Need to use the 5V level-shifted PWM2 pin on the shield
- MAY CAUSE SHIVERING/STUTTERING SERVO POSITION
- Were not quite sure why
6
How to generate a PWM signal: With a standard T/C
Not recommended for this exercise, but m entioned for context
As you know, T/Cs are very ve rsatile
Generally capture/compare mode, but "waveform" in Atmel
Prescaler sets/gives the PWM frequency
Compare value sets/gives the duty cycle
Map between PWM params and typical T/C params is not 1-1, requires a
bit of thinking.
To avoid thinking, Atmel has disguised a T/C as a dedicated PWM
peripheral.
7
How to generate a PWM signal: With the PWM peri pheral
Dedicated peripheral for generating PWM signals
Important registers:
- PWM->PWM_CLK / REG_PWM_CLK : PWM Clock register. Sets a prescaler, not required
- PWM->PWM_CH_NUM[n] .PWM_CMR / REG_PWM_CMRn : PWM Channel Mode Register
- PWM->PWM_CH_NUM[n] .PWM_CPRD / REG_PWM_CPRDn : PW M Channel Period Register
- PWM->PWM_CH_NUM[n] .PWM_CDTY / REG_PWM_CDTYn : PW M Channel Duty Cycle Register
- PWM->PWM_ENA / PWM_ENA : PWM Enable Register
- Multiple names for ea ch register (/), dened in th e sam cong directory.

9
Exercise 7: IR Beam Score System
The current through the photo-diode is dependent on the amount of light
received.
To measure the current, we need a resistor to measure the voltage over.
Choose the resistor value based on the information given in the
photo-diodes datasheet.
10
IR Schematic
11
Connecting the IR Circu itry
Use a voltage follower (op-amp).
Use the small bread-board.
Connect it as close to the photo-diode as possible to increase noise
immunity.
Check that the IR diode is working using a digital camera (e.g. mobile
phone pointed directly towards the top of the diode).
Do not connect to MCU before verifying voltage level compliance [0, 3.3]
- You will use the internal ADC of the ATSAM3X8E (datasheet chapter 43)
- Find a pin with an ADC peripheral that is not us ed elsewhere.
- Table 9-2 in the datasheet is a good start ing point.
12
Using the ADC Peripheral
Not A/B peripheral, but extra. See datasheet section 43.5.3 for activation.
Multiple modes supported, single ended freerun mode is th e easiest .
Important registers:
- ADC_MR : ADC Mode Register
- ADC_CHER : AD C Channel Enable Register
- ADC_CR : ADC Control Register
- ADC_CDR[n] : ADC Channel n Data Register
- ADC_LCDR : AD C Last Converted Data Register

15
Timer counter: Reading Motor Encoder
Internal 32-bit counter, TC2 CH0
Encoder mode: Channel is externally
driven
Important registers:
- TC_CV: Current count value
- TC_BMR: Channel mode register
- TC_CCR: Channel control register
Overow vs physical end points
Timer counters are everywhere: PWM,
RTCs, interrupts, encoders... Learn them!
16
Allegro A3959 motor driver: Motor Actuation
ENABLE: Activate motor
DIR: ...with the given polarity
PWM on Enable for speed control, DIR
for direction
Duty cycle determines speed, motor acts
as a low pass lter
Should be able to reuse code from servo
control

Position Contro ller
The quadrature encoder will give
an indication of the motor
position.
The error is the dierence
between the indicated position
and the desired position (from the
joystick).
Calculate controller constants.
Sum all values and apply to motor.
AVR221: Discrete PID Controller
on tinyAVR and m egaAVR Devices
Regular timing is important for
stability.
Hint: timer counter interrupt
18
Solenoid
The solenoid requires 12V (at least) to throw a
punch -> relay is a possible solution.
The ATSAM I/O pins can not supply the necessary
current to drive the relay -> transistor.
Protective diode at the relay input.
- Free-wheeling diode.
If your node 2 is resetting, chances are you are
not using free-wheeling diode.
While 3.3V works, the sole noid works better at 5V.
Use multiple channels on your lab supply and
ensure that Node 2 does not get 5V if you use
5V on yo ur solenoid.

Motor driver: unknown error mode where it stops working and possibly
gets hot. Write down what you did and tell us!

are connected. Dont do that.
Servo 5V regulator: Gets quite hot, handle with care.
